name: John
about:
Last year I set aside a pile of 12 books, and told myself that I wouldn't buy any more until I finished those 12. I made it through 9 before I broke down. This year, I picked out 25.

Granted, I already picked up a book from the library and borrowed one from a friend, but it isn't the same as buying.

name: Miguel Rodriguez
about:
I wrote this for my best friend who tragically passed away on July 7th, 2007. I had reservations about posting this here, but Micki always encouraged me to gain readers for what I wrote. I think she would want this to be shared.

Johanna Michelle "Micki" Blakely

Writing was something that Micki and I understood, despite our mutual lack of confidence in the craft. I shared with her what I would never share with anyone. She loved poetry, so I wrote her a poem. I hope it at least comes close to doing her justice. Either way, she would have told me it was beautiful and that she knew all my heart was in it. Then she would probably offer suggestions, which is something I still want her to do so badly. I called it:

All Things to All People

Rain was threat'ning; ready to fall.
And that kept her far
when last we spoke.
My mem'ry struggles to hear her voice that day
like playing tug-of-war
with a silk rope
and greasy hands.
But I manage to hold on
and recall so much more.

Micki was replete with duality.
One could feel among highest clouds
with her,
or smaller than an ant in a hole.
So cool she could refresh the parched;
so scorching, she could singe.
Resilient against all that cross'd her.
So like a dandelion in vulnerability,
She could be toss'd
By a child's breath.
Her laugh was as passionate
as full of emotion
as her tears.

The breeze and the hurricane.

How could she have been?
This woman with the
most stubborn ego,
yet so blind to all that made her
so singular
so indescribably beautiful.

One could say
she was a boiling mass of contradiction.
I know she was
all things to all people.
She was.
is.
will always be.
everything.
